*Where multiple aircraft types are operated, this training shall cover all relevant aircraft-specifi ifferences in safety equipment and/or safety and security procedures.

The Operator shall ensure cabin crew members complete practical training exercises consisting o abin drills and hands-on operation of cabin equipment. As a minimum, focus areas within the scop f practical training exercises shall include:

	(i) Cabin exit operations (normal and emergency) for each aircraft and exit type;

	(ii) Cabin emergency evacuation;

	(iii) If the operator uses aircraft equipped with cabin doors that have emergency egress slides:

		(a) Initial training: Use of emergency egress slide(s);

		(b) Requalification and recurrent training: Use of emergency egress slide(s) i ccordance with requirements of the Authority.

	(iv) Firefighting;

	(v) Oxygen administration;

	(vi) If required, ditching.

If the Operator uses pressurized aircraft, the Operator shall ensure cabin crew members receiv raining in high altitude depressurization. Such training shall provide:

	(i) An understanding of the effects on crew and passengers;

	(ii) The knowledge necessary to execute associated emergency procedures.

The Operator shall ensure cabin crew members receive training that provides knowledge in first ai nd inflight medical events. As a minimum, subjects within the scope of first aid training include:

	(i) Life-threatening medical emergencies;

	(ii) Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR);

	(iii) Management of injuries;

	(iv) Management of illnesses;

	(v) First-aid equipment and supplies;

	(vi) If applicable, medical equipment and supplies.

The Operator shall ensure cabin crew members complete initial and recurrent security training a pproved or accepted by the State, and in accordance with the Operator's security training progra s specified in SEC 2.1.1 . Cabin crew security training shall address the following subject areas:

	(i) Determination of the seriousness of any occurrence;

	(ii) Causes of disruptive behavior on board and management of such types of incidents;

	(iii) Crew communication and coordination;

	(iv) Policy and procedures associated with flight deck access;

	(v) Appropriate self-defense responses;

	(vi) Use of non-lethal protective devices assigned to crew members for use as authorized by th tate;

	(vii) Understanding the behavior of terrorists so as to facilitate the ability to cope with hijacke ehavior and passenger responses;

	(viii) Situational training exercises regarding various threat conditions;

	(ix) Flight deck procedures to protect the aircraft; 

	(x) Aircraft search procedures;

	(xi) As practicable, guidance on least-risk bomb locations.

The Operator shall specify and require a minimum number of cabin crew members for each aircraf ype to ensure a safe and expeditious aircraft evacuation and to perform the necessary functions i n emergency. Such minimum cabin crew specification(s) shall:

	(i) Be based on aircraft seating capacity or number of passengers carried;

	(ii) Be in accordance with minimum cabin crew requirements of the Authority;

	(iii) If the Operator has procedures for a temporary reduction of minimum cabin cre omplement during a case of incapacitation or unforeseen circumstances at a stopover(layover) point where a replacement cannot be obtained, require such procedures to b pproved or accepted by the Authority.

If the Operator uses an FRMS to manage cabin crew fatigue-related safety risks, the Operator shal ncorporate scientific principles and knowledge within the FRMS, comply with any applicabl equirements for managing cabin crew fatigue as established by the State or Authority and, as  inimum:

	(i) Define and document the FRMS policy;

	(ii) Incorporate risk management processes for fatigue hazard identification, risk assessmen nd risk mitigation;

	(iii) Develop and maintain effective FRMS safety assurance processes;

	(iv) Establish and implement effective FRMS promotion processes.

The Operator shall consider the following as duty time for the purpose of determining required res eriods and calculating duty time limitations for operating cabin crew members:

	(i) Entire duration of the flight;

	(ii) Pre-operating deadhead time;

	(iii) Training period(s) immediately prior to a flight;

	(iv) Administrative or office time immediately prior to a flight (for cabin crew members that serv n a management function).

The Operator shall have a policy that ensures cabin crew members, prior to being assigned to duty,
will not be affected by factors that could impair human performance. Such factors include, as  inimum:

	(i) Pregnancy;

	(ii) Illness, surgery or use of medication(s);

	(iii) Blood donation;

	(iv) Deep underwater diving.

The Operator shall have procedures to ensure a coordinated and expeditious cabin evacuatio uring aircraft fueling operations with passengers embarking, on board or disembarking. As  inimum, procedures shall require:

	(i) Cabin exits are designated for rapid deplaning or emergency evacuation, and routes to suc xits are unobstructed;

	(ii) The area outside designated emergency evacuation exits is unobstructed;

	(iii) One cabin crew member or other qualified person is positioned by the boarding door(s);

	(iv) Means of communication are established among cabin crew members and with passengers;

	(v) A suitable method of communication is established between qualified persons that monito assenger safety and personnel that have responsibility for fueling operations.

The Operator shall have a procedure to ensure the cabin crew verifies that:

	(i) Passenger and crew baggage in the passenger cabin is securely stowed;

	(ii) If applicable, cargo packages and/or passenger items being transported in passenger seat re properly secured.

The Operator shall have procedures for the opening and closing of aircraft cabin access doors durin ormal operations. Such procedures shall define:

	(i) Who is responsible for opening and closing aircraft cabin access doors;

	(ii) When doors should be opened and closed;

	(iii) Appropriate methods of communication and/or coordination between the cabin or flight cre nd ground personnel to ensure safety is maintained during normal door operations.

The Operator shall require cabin crew members to be seated with their safety harness fastened:

	(i) During the takeoff and landing phases of flight;

	(ii) Whenever the pilot-in-command (PIC) so directs.

If the Operator uses movable carts or trolleys for passenger service in the aircraft cabin, the Operato hall:

	(i) Ensure such carts or trolleys are equipped with braking devices;

	(ii) Have a process to ensure braking devices are operative;

	(iii) Have procedures to ensure unserviceable carts or trolleys are withdrawn for repair o eplacement.

If the Operator uses movable carts or trolleys for passenger service in the aircraft cabin, the Operato hall have procedures to ensure such carts or trolleys are:

	(i) Stowed during the takeoff and landing phases of flight;

	(ii) Stowed when not in use;

	(iii) Stowed if feasible, or secured, during an emergency situation;

	(iv) Stowed if feasible, or secured, prior to or during turbulence;

	(v) Secured with braking device engaged at any time when stationary;

	(vi) Attended by cabin crew when used within the passenger cabin.

The Operator shall have a policy and associated procedures that define a sterile flight deck durin ritical phases of flight, to include:

	(i) A procedure for communication between the cabin crew and flight crew;

	(ii) A procedure for notification of the flight crew in the event of an emergency.

If the Operator uses aircraft equipped with a flight deck door, the Operator shall have policies and/o rocedures that are in accordance with requirements of the Authority and, as a minimum, define:

	(i) When the flight deck door must remain locked;

	(ii) The means used and actions necessary for cabin crew members to:

		(a) Notify the flight crew in the event of suspicious activity or security breaches in th abin;

		(b) Gain entry to the flight deck.

The Operator shall have procedures for communication and coordination between the cabin cre nd flight crew to ensure a combined and coordinated process in addressing:

	(i) Passenger safety information;

	(ii) Cabin readiness prior to first aircraft movement, takeoff and landing;

	(iii) Arming or disarming of cabin door slides or slide rafts, if applicable;

	(iv) Preparation for and an encounter with turbulence;

	(v) Medical situations;

	(vi) Flight or cabin crew member incapacitation;

	(vii) Emergency evacuation;

	(viii) Abnormal situations;

	(ix) Emergency situations.

The Operator shall have procedures that ensure the cabin crew is notified:

	(i) When to be seated and secure themselves for takeoff;

	(ii) When the flight is in the descent phase;

	(iii) When to be seated and secure themselves for landing.

The Operator shall have a policy and procedures for the acceptance or non-acceptance, as well a nboard handling, of passengers who might require special handling by the cabin crew. Such polic nd procedures shall be in accordance with applicable regulations and, as a minimum, address:

	(i) Passengers with disabilities or reduced mobility;

	(ii) Passengers with injuries or illness;

	(iii) Persons on stretchers;

	(iv) Infants and children, including unaccompanied children (UMNR) if accepted;

	(v) Inadmissible passengers, deportees, or persons in custody.

The Operator shall have a policy and associated procedures for addressing passengers that exhibi nruly behavior and/or interfere with a crew member prior to or during flight. Such policy an rocedures shall be in accordance with local laws and regulations, and also specify reasonabl easures for ensuring passengers obey lawful commands from the PIC and/or cabin crew for th urpose of securing the safety of the aircraft, persons on board and their property. As a minimum, th olicy and procedures shall address:

	(i) Identification of passenger unruly behavior and interference;

	(ii) Identification of passengers showing signs of intoxication, whether from alcohol or othe ubstances, which might contribute to unruly behavior and interference;

	(iii) Conditions under which passengers may be denied boarding, disembarked or restrained i ccordance with the authority of the PIC;

	(iv) Reporting of instances of unruly behavior.

The Operator shall have cabin crew procedures that require all passengers to be seated with thei eat belts (or harness or other restraint provided) fastened:

	(i) For the taxi, takeoff and landing phases of a flight;

	(ii) Prior to and/or during turbulence;

	(iii) When the PIC considers it necessary for the safety of the flight.

The Operator shall have guidance and associated cabin crew procedures to ensure passengers:

	(i) Are informed and receive instruction on all restrictions pertaining to onboard smoking;

	(ii) Comply with the Fasten Seat Belt sign and, if applicable, the No Smoking sign.

The Operator shall have cabin crew procedures and guidance to ensure passengers are familiar wit ocation and use of:

	(i) Seat belts;

	(ii) Emergency exits;

	(iii) Life jackets (individual flotation devices), if required;

	(iv) Oxygen masks, where applicable;

	(v) Other emergency equipment provided for individual use, including safety informatio ards.

The Operator shall have a cabin crew policy and procedures that ensure, as applicable to aircraf ype and configuration, the delivery of oxygen to passengers:

	(i) Immediately following a depressurization;

	(ii) For treatment during a medical event where oxygen is required.

The Operator shall have procedures to ensure the availability, accessibility and serviceability o ircraft cabin emergency systems and equipment for passenger flights. Such procedures shal nclude a preflight inspection of systems and equipment, which, as a minimum, shall be conducted b he cabin crew or, if applicable, by the flight crew prior to the first flight:

	(i) After a new cabin crew has assumed control of the aircraft cabin unless there is a procedur or an onboard handover briefing (e.g. during transit stops) between a departing/inboun rew and a replacement/outbound crew that includes verification of the status of emergenc ystems and equipment;

	(ii) After an aircraft has been left unattended by a flight crew or cabin crew for any period of tim nless the Operator has a process or procedure that ensures cabin emergency systems an quipment remain undisturbed while crew members are temporarily absent from th abin.

If the Operator conducts passenger flights with or without cabin crew, the Operator shall ensure al assenger aircraft in its fleet are provisioned with a safety information card accessible to eac assenger, which contains appropriate information, instructions, restrictions or locations relevant to:

	(i) Seat belts;

	(ii) Emergency exits;

	(iii) If applicable, emergency escape path lighting;

	(iv) Life jackets (personal flotation devices), if required;

	(v) Passenger oxygen masks;

	(vi) Smoking restrictions.

The Operator should ensure all passenger aircraft in its fleet are equipped with one or more universa recaution kits for use by cabin crew members in managing:

	(i) Episodes of ill health associated with a case of suspected communicable disease;

	(ii) Cases of illness involving contact with body fluids.
